[[File:Ptolemy Asia detail.jpg|thumb|300px|The 11th Asian regional map from [[Claudius Ptolemy|Ptolemy]]'s ''[[Ptolemy's Geography|Geography]]'' ([[Harleian MS&nbsp;7182]])]]
The '''Magnus Sinus''' or '''Sinus Magnus''' ([[Latin]]; {{lang-grc-gre|ὀ Μέγας Κόλπος}}, ''o Mégas Kólpos''),{{sfnp|Ptolemy|c. 150|loc=Vol.&nbsp;VII, §3 & 5}}{{sfn|Agathemerus|loc=Vol.&nbsp;I, p.&nbsp;53}} also [[anglicization of names|anglicized]] as the {{nowrap|'''Great Gulf''',}} was the form of the [[Gulf of Thailand]] and [[South China Sea]] known to [[Greek geographers|Greek]], [[Roman geographers|Roman]], [[medieval Arab geographers|Arab]], [[medieval Persian geographers|Persian]], and [[Renaissance cartographers]] before the [[Age of Discovery]]. It was then briefly conflated with the [[Pacific Ocean]] before disappearing from maps.
__NOTOC__

==History==
{{further|Sino-Roman relations|Daqin|Chinese cartography|Chinese geography}}
The gulf and its major port of [[Cattigara]] had supposedly been reached by a 1st-century [[Ancient Greeks|Greek]] trader named Alexander, who returned safely and left a [[periplus]] of his voyage.{{sfnp|Glover|2005}} His account that Cattigara was "some days" sail from [[Zaba (Ptolemy)|Zaba]] was taken by [[Marinus of Tyre|Marinus]] of [[Tyre (city)|Tyre]] to mean "numberless" days and by [[Ptolemy]] to mean "a few".{{sfnp|Suárez|1999|p=99}}{{refn|group=note|"Marinus does not exhibit the mileage from the [[Golden Chersonese]] to [[Cattigara]]. But he says that Alexander has described the land beyond to lie facing the south, and that after sailing by this for 20 days you reach the city of Zaba, and still saying on for some days southward but rather to the left [i.e., east] you reach Cattigara. He exaggerates the distance, for the expression is ''some days'' not ''many days''. He says indeed that no numerical statement of the days was made because they were so many: but this I take to be ridiculous."{{refn|Ptolemy,{{sfnp|Ptolemy|c. 150}} translated by Yule.{{sfnp|Yule|1866|p=cl}}}}}} Both Alexander and Marinus's works have been lost, but were claimed as authorities by Ptolemy in [[Ptolemy's Geography|his ''Geography'']].{{sfnp|Ptolemy|c. 150|loc=Vol.&nbsp;I, §14}} Ptolemy (and presumably Marinus before him) followed [[Hipparchus]] in making the [[Indian Ocean]] a landlocked sea, placing Cattigara on its [[terra incognita|unknown eastern shoreline]]. The expanse formed between it and the [[Malay Peninsula]] (the "[[Golden Chersonese]]"), he called the Great Gulf.{{sfnp|Bunbury|1911|p=625}}

<!-- [[WP:NFCC]] violation: [[File:Al-Khwarizmi's map.png|thumb|left|[[Hubert Dauntich|Dauntich]]'s reconstruction of the [[Indian Ocean]] area of [[al-Khwārizmī]]'s [[Book of the Description of the Earth|world map]], showing the replacement of the eastern shore of the Great Gulf with the [[Dragon's Tail (peninsula)|Dragon's Tail]]]] -->
[[Ptolemy's Geography|Ptolemy's ''Geography'']] was translated into [[Arabic language|Arabic]] by a team of scholars including [[al-Khwārizmī]] in the 9th century during the reign of [[al-Maʿmūn]]. By that time, Arab merchants such as [[Soleiman the Merchant|Soleiman]] had begun regular commerce with [[Tang China]] and, having passed through the [[Strait of Malacca]] ''en route'', shown that the Indian Sea communicated with the [[World Ocean|open ocean]]. African traders similarly showed{{citation needed|date=March 2015}} that the coastline did not turn sharply east south of [[Cape Prasum]] below [[Zanzibar]] as Ptolemy held.{{sfnp|Bunbury|1911|p=624}} [[Al-Khwārizmī]]'s influential ''[[Book of the Description of the Earth]]'', therefore, removed Ptolemy's unknown shores from the Indian Ocean. The robustly-described lands east of the Great Gulf, however, were retained as a phantom peninsula (now generally known as the [[Dragon's Tail (peninsula)|Dragon's Tail]]).

Just after 1295, [[Maximus Planudes]] restored Ptolemy's Greek text and maps at [[Chora Monastery]] in [[Constantinople]] ([[Istanbul]]). This was translated into Latin at [[Republic of Florence|Florence]] by [[Jacobus Angelus]] around 1406 and quickly spread the work's information and misinformation throughout Western Europe. The maps initially repeated Ptolemy's enclosed Indian Sea. Following word of [[Bartholomew Dias]]'s circumnavigation of Africa, maps by [[Henricus Martellus|Martellus]] and by [[Martin of Bohemia]] replaced this with a new form of the [[Dragon's Tail peninsula]], including details from [[Il Milione|Marco Polo]]. As early as 1540, [[Age of Discovery|continuing exploration]] led [[Sebastian Münster]] to conflate the Great Gulf with the [[Pacific Ocean]] west of the [[Americas]], supposing that the 1st-century Alexander had crossed to a port in [[Viceroyalty of Peru|Peru]] and safely returned.{{sfnp|Suárez|1999|p=99}} The idea was repeated by [[Ortelius]] and others.{{sfnp|Suárez|1999|p=71}} (Some modern [[South America]]n scholars have returned to the idea as recently as the 1990s, but there remains no substantial evidence to support the idea.{{sfnp|Richardson|2003}}) The Great Gulf was finally dispensed with in all its forms as more accurate accounts returned from both the [[East Indies|East]] and [[West Indies]].

[[File:DAnville Cattigara 1794.jpg|thumb|right|A detail from an 18th-century map showing the common identification of the Great Gulf with the Gulf of Thailand{{sfnp|d'Anville|1763}}]]

==Details==
The details of the Great Gulf changed somewhat among its various forms, but the ancient and Renaissance [[Ptolemy's Geography|Ptolemaic accounts]] had it bound on the west by the [[Golden Chersonese]] and on the north and east by the ports of the [[Sinae]], chief among which was [[Cattigara]].{{sfnp|Vaux|1854b}} [[Medieval Islamic cartographers]] followed [[al-Khwārizmī]] in having a strait southeast of the gulf communicating with the [[Sea of Darkness]]. Believing the [[circumference of the Earth]] to follow Ptolemy's reduced figures or even smaller ones, cartographers during the early phases of the [[Age of Discovery]] expanded the Gulf to form the [[Pacific Ocean]] west of [[South America]], considered to represent a [[Dragon's Tail (peninsula)|southeastern peninsula]] of Asia.

Modern reconstructions agree in naming the [[Golden Chersonese]] a form of the [[Malaysian Peninsula]] but differ in their considerations of how much of the [[South China Sea]] to include within Ptolemy's reckoning of the Great Gulf. Those following Alexander's route from Zaba on its northern shore to Cattigara to its southeast consider it to be no more than the [[Gulf of Thailand]], with Cattigara located in the [[Kingdom of Funan|Funanese]] [[Óc Eo]] ruins at [[Thoại Sơn]]. Its [[Cottiaris River]] would then be a former course of the [[Mekong River|Mekong]] which once passed the site to enter the [[Gulf of Thailand]].{{sfnp|Herrmann|1938}}{{sfnp|Malleret|1962}}{{sfnp|Glover|2005}} Others ignoring the route as garbled but taking Cattigara to be the major [[Han Empire|Han]] entrepôt of [[Longbian Commandery|Longbian]] consider the Great Gulf to have been the [[Gulf of Tonkin]], hypothesizing that the Gulf of Thailand (if present) was represented by the smaller inlet on the eastern shore of the Golden Chersonese. Its Cottiaris River would have been [[Vietnam]]'s [[Red River (Vietnam)|Red River]]. [[Panyu]] ([[Guangzhou]]) had been the major port of the [[Kingdom of Nanyue]] but identifications of Ptolemy's Cattigara with Han-era [[Nanhai Commandery|Nanhai]], though common in the past,{{sfnp|Smith|1854}}{{sfnp|Vaux|1854a}} are credited little more than those placing it in Peru.

