'''Margaret Hubbard''' (16 June 1924 – 28 April 2011) was an Australian-born British [[classical scholar]] specialising in [[philology]]. From 1957 to 1986, she was a [[Tutorial system|tutor]] and [[Fellow (Oxbridge)|Fellow]] of [[St Anne's College, Oxford]].<ref name="Founding Fellows">{{cite web|title=Founding Fellows - Margaret Hubbard|url=http://www.st-annes.ox.ac.uk/about/history/founding-fellows/margaret-hubbard|website=St Anne’s College|publisher=University of Oxford|accessdate=14 January 2017}}</ref> She has been described as "one of the most distinguished classical scholars of the modern age".<ref name="Times obit">{{cite news|title=Margaret Hubbard|url=http://www.thetimes.co.uk/tto/opinion/obituaries/article3017588.ece|accessdate=14 January 2017|work=The Times|date=13 May 2011}}</ref> Hubbard was one of St Anne's College's 15 founding fellows.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.st-annes.ox.ac.uk/about/history/founding-fellows|title=St Anne's College, Oxford > About the College > Founding Fellows|website=www.st-annes.ox.ac.uk|language=en|access-date=2017-07-21}}</ref>
A one-day conference was held to commemorate Hubbard, and in her will she gave money to fund the college's Fellowship in Classical Languages and Literature, named after her father, A.E. Hubbard.<ref>{{citation |title=Annual Review 2011 |publisher=St Anne's College |url=http://www.st-annes.ox.ac.uk/fileadmin/documents/Publications/St-Annes_Annual_Review_Review_2011.pdf |pages=14, 19}}</ref>
