{{Infobox settlement | name = Ngodo | settlement_type = Archaeological site | pushpin_map = Nigeria |coordinates = {{coord|5|51|21|N|7|30|43|E|display=inline,title}} | elevation_m = }} '''Ngodo''' is an Igbo community in [[Uturu]], [[Isuikwuato Local Government Area]], [[Abia State]] in [[Nigeria]] which houses a stone age site that provides evidence that humans inhabited the region as far back as 250,000&nbsp;years ago. It was the largest handaxe factory in Nigeria, and possibly in the world.<ref name=Uzukwu1997/> <ref>Ikechukwu Joshua Okonkwo, Umuakam kindred, Ngodo</ref>
The site at NGODO-Uturu, which lies on a [[dolerite]] ridge, was excavated between 1977 and 1981.<ref name=Shaw1999/> Archaeologists were led to the site by local people who were aware of the unusual artifacts to be found.<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=dhk9AAAAIAAJ&pg=PA107 |page=107 |title=Approaches to the archaeological heritage: a comparative study of world cultural resource management systems |author=Henry Cleere |publisher=Cambridge University Press |year=1984 |ISBN=0-521-24305-X}}</ref> The northern end of the site held a huge accumulation of stone-age artifacts up to 6&nbsp;meters in depth. There was no pottery and no polished stone tools, but there were triangular preforms for bifacial tools as well as many flakes and some cores. Handaxes, mostly broken, accounted for four out of five of the tools, and there were also cleavers, picks and sidescrapers. Based on this mix, the site has been classified as [[Acheulean]]. It is possible that these tools were rough or unsuccessful attempts, and the successful tools were carried elsewhere to be refined further.<ref name=Shaw1999/>
There are three layers of occupation. The oldest and lowest holds quartz flakes, small stone tools and points. Above that is a layer with hoe-like tools, polished stone axes, red ochre, bored stone and red pottery. The top level, with dates between 2935&nbsp;BC and 15&nbsp;AD, held grey pottery wares.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.iweadighi.com/uploads/media/Origin_or_Genealogy_of_the_Igbo_people_of_Nigeria.pdf |title=Origin or Genealogy of the Igbo people of Nigeria |author=Sabinus Iweadighi |publisher=University of Vienna |accessdate=2011-01-09}}</ref>
==References== {{reflist|1|refs= <ref name=Shaw1999>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=8HKDtlPuM2oC&pg=PA594 |page=594 |chapter=Ngodo-Uturu |title=A dictionary of archaeology |author=Ian Shaw, Robert Jameson |publisher=John Wiley and Sons |year=1999 |ISBN=0-631-17423-0}}</ref> <ref name=Uzukwu1997>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=9hhmzVrYPHAC&pg=PA92 |page=92 |title=Worship as body language: introduction to Christian worship : an African orientation |author=E. Elochukwu Uzukwu |publisher=Liturgical Press |year=1997 |ISBN=0-8146-6151-3}}</ref> }}
